Other names in common use for the Cholas are Killi (&lt;U+0B95&gt;&lt;U+0BBF&gt;&lt;U+0BB3&gt;&lt;U+0BCD&gt;&lt;U+0BB3&gt;&lt;U+0BBF&gt;), Valavan (&lt;U+0BB5&gt;&lt;U+0BB3&gt;&lt;U+0BB5&gt;&lt;U+0BA9&gt;&lt;U+0BCD&gt;) and Sembiyan (&lt;U+0B9A&gt;&lt;U+0BC7&gt;&lt;U+0BAE&gt;&lt;U+0BCD&gt;&lt;U+0BAA&gt;&lt;U+0BBF&gt;&lt;U+0BAF&gt;&lt;U+0BA9&gt;&lt;U+0BCD&gt;). Killi perhaps comes from the Tamil kil (&lt;U+0B95&gt;&lt;U+0BBF&gt;&lt;U+0BB3&gt;&lt;U+0BCD&gt;) meaning dig or cleave and conveys the idea of a digger or a worker of the land. This word often forms an integral part of early Chola names like Nedunkilli, Nalankilli and so on, but almost drops out of use in later times. Valavan is most probably connected with 'valam' (&lt;U+0BB5&gt;&lt;U+0BB3&gt;&lt;U+0BAE&gt;&lt;U+0BCD&gt;) &lt;U+2013&gt; fertility and means owner or ruler of a fertile country. Sembiyan is generally taken to mean a descendant of Shibi &lt;U+2013&gt; a legendary hero whose self-sacrifice in saving a dove from the pursuit of a falcon figures among the early Chola legends and forms the subject matter of the Sibi Jataka among the Jataka stories of Buddhism. K.A. Nilakanta Sastri, The C&lt;U+014D&gt;&lt;U+013B&gt;as, pp 19–20↩
