17th century Italian traveler Pietro Della Valle (1623) has given a vivid account of the village schools in South India. These accounts reflect the system of primary education in existence until the morder times in Tamil Nadu↩
Rajendra Chola I endowed a large college in which more than 280 students learnt from 14 teachers - K.A. Nilakanta Sastri, A History of South India, p 293↩
The students studied a number of subjects in these colleges, including philosophy (anvikshiki), Vedas (trayi &lt;U+2013&gt; the threefold Vedas of Rigveda, Yajurveda and Samaveda. The fourth Atharvaveda was considered a non-religious text.), economics (vartta), government (dandaniti), grammar, prosody, etymology, astronomy, logic (tarka), medicine (ayurveda), politics (arthasastra) and music. - K.A. Nilakanta Sastri, A History of South India, p 292↩
